SIMPLE: clown
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Clown
<hw>Clown</hw> <pr>(kloun)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Icel.
<ets>klunni</ets> a clumsy, boorish fellow, North Fries.
<ets>kl⟦oum⟧nne</ets> clown, dial. Sw. <ets>klunn</ets> log, Dan.
<ets>klunt</ets> log, block, and E. <ets>clump</ets>, n.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A man of coarse nature and manners; an awkward fellow;
an ill-bred person; a boor.</def> <rj><au>Sir P. Sidney.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One who works upon the soil; a rustic; a
churl.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>clown</qex>, the child of nature, without guile.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The fool or buffoon in a play, circus,
etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>clown</qex> shall make those laugh whose lungs are tickle
o'the sere.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Clown</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Clown
<hw>Clown</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To act as a clown; -- with
<xex>it</xex>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Beshrew me, he <qex>clowns</qex> it properly indeed.</q>
<rj><qau>B. Jonson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Clownage</ent>⟦br⟧
